    "experimental_data": {
      "key_results": "All formulations met compendial requirements. Double-layer tablets provided immediate release from the outer layer (within 45 seconds) and sustained release from the core. The slowest release was from PVP K90-based cores. Release was governed by the Higuchi model. Carbomer-based cores showed Supercase II transport due to high swelling, while others showed non-Fickian diffusion/erosion.",
      "statistical_analysis": "One-way ANOVA was used to determine differences in release profiles, swelling, and erosion data (p < 0.05). Significant differences were found among release profiles of all core formulations."
    }
  },
  "conclusion": "The conclusion is on Pages 7 and 8. It states that double-layer tablets with cores based on HPMC and HPMC-PVP mixtures displayed better flow and compression properties. Although PVP K90 and carbomer cores had poor flow, the final double-layer tablets had desired physical characteristics. The study concluded that these double-layer tablets could reduce dosing frequency and improve patient compliance in treating inflammatory conditions."
